{{Infobox military person | name = Manuel Komnenos | native_name = Μανουήλ Κομνηνός | native_name_lang = grc | image = Seal of Manuel Komnenos, kouropalates.jpg | caption = Lead seal of Manuel Komnenos with his title of ''[[kouropalates]]'', showing the [[military saints]] [[Demetrius of Thessalonica]] and [[Saint George]] | birth_date = {{circa|1045}} | death_date = 17 April 1071 | birth_place = | death_place = | rank = | battles = Campaigns against the [[Seljuq Turks|Seljuq]] raids into [[Asia Minor]] | battles_label = | spouse = | relations = [[John Komnenos (Domestic of the Schools)|John Komnenos]] (father), [[Alexios I Komnenos]] and [[Isaac Komnenos (brother of Alexios I)|Isaac Komnenos]] (brothers) }} '''Manuel Komnenos''' ({{Lang-gr|Μανουήλ Κομνηνός}}, ''Manouēl Komnēnos''; {{circa|1045}} – 17 April 1071) was a [[Byzantine Empire|Byzantine]] aristocrat and military leader, the oldest son of [[John Komnenos (Domestic of the Schools)|John Komnenos]] and brother of emperor [[Alexios I Komnenos]]. A relative by marriage of emperor [[Romanos IV Diogenes]], he was placed in charge of expeditions against [[Seljuq Turks|Turkish]] raids in 1070–1071, until his sudden death by illness in April 1071.
==Life and career== Manuel was the first-born child of [[John Komnenos (Domestic of the Schools)|John Komnenos]], and his wife [[Anna Dalassene]].{{sfn|Varzos|1984|p=61}} The date of his birth is unknown, but he was described as a youth in 1068, so he must have been born around 1045.{{sfn|Varzos|1984|p=61}} Already as a child, as was customary for children of the Byzantine aristocracy, he was trained in war by his father, who at the time was ''[[domestikos ton scholon]]'' (commander-in-chief) of the Eastern field army.{{sfn|Varzos|1984|p=61 (note 4)}} By 1068 Manuel held the high court rank of ''[[protoproedros]]''. In that year he married a relative of Emperor [[Romanos IV Diogenes]] ({{reign|1068|1071}}), who on the occasion raised him further to ''[[kouropalates]]'' and appointed him to the military post of ''[[protostrator]]''.{{sfn|Varzos|1984|pp=61–62}} The couple had at least one daughter, most likely named Anna after Manuel's mother.{{sfn|Varzos|1984|pp=63–64}}
As ''protostrator'', Manuel confronted the raids of the [[Seljuq Turks]] into eastern [[Asia Minor]]. In one such skirmish in 1070, he foolhardily pressed ahead to the Turkish camp, and was captured after a bitter struggle. His loss led to the defeat of his army and the capture of his two lieutenants and brothers-in-law, [[Michael Taronites]] and [[Nikephoros Melissenos]].{{sfn|Varzos|1984|pp=62–63}} Brought before the Turkish leader, a certain [[Chrysoskoulos]], Manuel managed to inflame his ambition and raise him in revolt against his nominal sovereign, [[Sultan]] [[Alp Arslan]] ({{reign|1063|1072}}). Indeed, Chrysoskoulos accompanied his captives to the Byzantine capital, [[Constantinople]], where Romanos IV received them with much honour.{{sfn|Varzos|1984|p=63}}
In spring 1071, Manuel and Chrysoskoulos went on campaign together against the Seljuqs, but on the way Manuel fell heavily ill with an [[ear infection]] in [[Bithynia]]. His mother hurried to his side at the monastery of Theotokos of Alypos on Mt. Azalas, but arrived barely in time for him to bid her farewell before he died.{{sfn|Varzos|1984|p=63}} According to the late 12th-century ''[[typikon]]'' of the [[Monastery of Christ Philanthropos]], founded by Empress [[Irene Doukaina]], wife of Manuel's younger brother [[Alexios I Komnenos]] ({{reign|1081|1118}}),{{sfn|Kouroupou|Vannier|2005|pp=41ff.}} he died on 17 April (the day of his commemoration).{{sfn|Kouroupou|Vannier|2005|p=60}} In the ''typikon'', he is listed as a ''[[sebastos]]'', but this is an anachronism reflecting later practice.{{sfn|Kouroupou|Vannier|2005|p=60}}
