'''Techno-economic assessment''' (abbreviated '''TEA''') is a [[methodology]] framework to analyze the technical and [[Economics|economic]] performance of a [[Business process|process]], [[Product (business)|product]] or [[Service (economics)|service]].<ref>{{cite conference  | url = https://aiche.confex.com/aiche/2018/meetingapp.cgi/Paper/535169 | title =  Guidelines for Techno-Economic Assessment of Carbon Capture and Utilization Technologies | last1 = Zimmermann et al. | first1 = Arno W. | date = 30 October 2018 | location = Pittsburgh, PA, USA | conference = American Institute of Chemical Engineers (AIChE) 2018 Annual Meeting }}</ref> TEA normally combines [[process modeling]], [[Engineering design process|engineering design]] and [[economic evaluation]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://abpdu.lbl.gov/capabilities/techno-economic-analysis/|title=Techno-Economic Analysis|last=|first=|date=|work=AB PDU|access-date=2018-10-09|language=en-US}}</ref>

Examples of applications of TEA include the evaluation of the economic feasibility of a specific [[project]], a forecast on the likelihood of the deployment of a [[technology]] at certain scale, or a comparison of the economic merit of different technological options that provide the same service.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Lauer |first1=Maximilan |title=Methodology guideline on techno  economic assessment (TEA) |publisher=Intelligent Energy Europe |url=https://ec.europa.eu/energy/intelligent/projects/sites/iee-projects/files/projects/documents/thermalnet_methodology_guideline_on_techno_economic_assessment.pdf}}</ref> 

